using System;
using System.Globalization;

public static class StringExtensions
{
    public static string ToTitleCase(this string input)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(input))
            return input;

        var words = input.Split((char[])null, StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
        for (int i = 0; i < words.Length; i++)
        {
            var word = words[i];
            if (word.Length == 0) continue;

            var firstChar = char.ToUpper(word[0], CultureInfo.CurrentCulture);
            var rest = word.Length > 1 ? word.Substring(1).ToLower(CultureInfo.CurrentCulture) : string.Empty;
            words[i] = firstChar + rest;
        }

        return string.Join(" ", words);
    }
}

### What is Dependency Injection (DI)?

Think of DI as a way to give a class the pieces it needs (its *dependencies*) **outside** of itself, instead of having the class create those pieces on its own.  
In ASP.NET Core, DI is built‑in and is the primary mechanism for managing object lifetimes, promoting loose coupling, and making unit testing easier.

---

## 1. Core Concepts

| Term | What it means in ASP.NET Core |
|------|------------------------------|
| **Service** | Any class that provides functionality (e.g., `ILogger`, `IRepository`, `IMailSender`). |
| **Service Provider** | The container that knows how to create services and resolve their dependencies. |
| **Service Lifetime** | Controls how long a service instance lives. Options: `Singleton`, `Scoped`, `Transient`. |
| **Constructor Injection** | The most common pattern: dependencies are passed as constructor parameters. |
| **Property / Method Injection** | Alternatives (less common) where dependencies are set on properties or passed to methods. |

---

## 2. Registering Services

All service registrations happen in the `Program.cs` (or `Startup.cs` in older templates) inside the `ConfigureServices` method.

```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    // 1. Singleton: one instance for the entire app
    services.AddSingleton<ILoggerFactory, LoggerFactory>();

    // 2. Scoped: one instance per HTTP request
    services.AddScoped<IUserRepository, UserRepository>();

    // 3. Transient: new instance each time requested
    services.AddTransient<IMailSender, SmtpMailSender>();

    // 4. Add framework services (MVC, Razor Pages, etc.)
    services.AddControllersWithViews();
}
```

- `IServiceCollection` is a list of service descriptors.
- The container will later use these descriptors to create objects when needed.

---

## 3. Resolving Services (Injecting Them)

### 3.1 Constructor Injection (the most common)

```csharp
public class HomeController : Controller
{
    private readonly IUserRepository _userRepo;
    private readonly IMailSender _mailSender;

    public HomeController(IUserRepository userRepo, IMailSender mailSender)
    {
        _userRepo = userRepo;
        _mailSender = mailSender;
    }

    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        var users = _userRepo.GetAll();
        _mailSender.Send("welcome@example.com", "Hello!", "Welcome to our site.");
        return View(users);
    }
}
```

- The framework automatically resolves `IUserRepository` and `IMailSender` when it creates `HomeController`.
- If you add a new dependency, just add it to the constructor; no extra code is needed.

### 3.2 Property Injection (rarely used)

```csharp
public class NotificationService
{
    [Inject] // custom attribute if you want to mark it
    public IMailSender MailSender { get; set; }

    public void Notify(string email, string message)
    {
        MailSender.Send(email, "Notification", message);
    }
}
```

- You would need to manually resolve the container and set the property, which is why constructor injection is preferred.

### 3.3 Method Injection (for specific scenarios)

```csharp
public void ProcessOrder(Order order, IOrderProcessor processor)
{
    processor.Process(order);
}
```

- Useful when a dependency is only needed for a single method call.

